<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The <a href="/research/custom-node-registry/">#2074 <code>customNodes</code></a> recipe model can express a
  region's <strong>open</strong> marker (<code>{{#if}}</code>, a <code>children:'inert'</code> recipe) and its
  <strong>close</strong> (<code>{{/if}}</code>, the name-echoed <code>regionClose</code>) — but it has
  <strong>no axis for the MID-region marker</strong> (<code>{{else}}</code>) that divides a region body into an
  if-segment and an else-segment. The gap was confirmed, not guessed, by the
  <a href="/backlog/2094-framework-flavored-delimiter-bundles/">#2094 delimiter-bundle</a> program: Handlebars
  <code>{{else}}</code> (#2114), Liquid/Jinja <code>{% else %}</code>/<code>{% elsif %}</code> (#2115), and
  Svelte <code>{:else}</code>/<code>{:else if}</code> (#2118) each scored the same structural gap. This is prep
  for decision <a href="/backlog/2201-mid-region-marker-else-decision-card/">#2201</a>: <em>how should the recipe
  model express the mid-marker?</em>
</p>

<h2>Code ground truth — the model has a binary region contract</h2>
<p>
  A region recipe materializes onto a <strong>single</strong> <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> host whose
  <code>.content</code> holds the whole region body
  (<code>fui:plugs/webnodes/recipes/RegionNode.ts:66</code>;
  <code>fui:plugs/webnodes/CustomNodeRegistry.ts:670</code>). The region walk is a <strong>binary
  match-stack</strong>: it pairs the open marker <code>{#each</code> (name-echo needle
  <code>open + regionName</code>) against exactly one close <code>{/each}</code>, balancing nesting depth
  (<code>fui:plugs/webnodes/CustomNodeRegistry.ts:714</code>). There is <strong>no third in-region token</strong>
  and no way to split <code>.content</code> into labelled sub-fragments — a <code>{{else}}</code> inside the body
  lands as inert literal text. The IDL axes are <code>static open</code>/<code>close</code>/<code>value</code>/<code>children</code>/<code>regionName</code>/<code>regionClose</code>
  (<code>we:src/_includes/spec-descriptions/plugs/customnoderegistry.njk:85-97</code>;
  <code>we:docs/agent/block-standard.md:578-584</code>) — and <code>children</code> is a <em>scalar enum of
  body-scan modes</em> (<code>'inert'</code>/<code>'live'</code>/<code>'raw'</code>), not a segment/program map.
  That absence is exactly the axis #2201 must decide.
</p>

<h2>Prior art — how mainstream engines model the mid-marker</h2>
<p>
  We surveyed the primary AST sources of the major template/markup systems. The result is decisive: the mainstream
  models a conditional block as <strong>one node carrying multiple <em>named body programs</em></strong>, and the
  mid-marker is merely the parse-time delimiter that decides which named program subsequent statements accumulate
  into. It is neither a scalar field nor a node in the output tree.
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
