<h2>The negative result — two options with zero prior art</h2>
<p>
  Two shapes a naive design might reach for appear in <strong>no</strong> surveyed engine — and they are exactly
  the #2201 card's original Fork 1 and Fork 2:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>A scalar <code>mid</code> field</strong> on the block node — no engine carries the mid-marker as a
    property; it is always a parse-time boundary between named programs.</li>
  <li><strong>A degenerate nested region</strong> (<code>{{#else}}…{{/else}}</code>) — no engine models the
    else-body as a child region of the if-region, and it does not reproduce real grammars (Handlebars' authored
    <code>{{else}}</code> is not <code>{{#else}}</code>).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Synthesis — the fourth design option</h2>
<p>
  The evidence yields a distinct, prior-art-grounded recipe shape the #2201 card's original three forks miss:
</p>
<blockquote>
  <strong>Labelled-segment bodies.</strong> A region is a <em>sequence of labelled segments split at
  mid-markers</em>. Instead of a single <code>.content</code>, the block node exposes a map of named body
  programs — <code>programs: { main, inverse }</code> (or <code>{ body, else }</code>) — where the mid-marker
  (<code>{{else}}</code>) is a parse-time delimiter that partitions the body, and is neither a scalar field nor a
  node in the output tree. Chained mid-markers (<code>{{else if}}</code>) are modelled by the trailing program
  containing a single nested block of the same kind (recursion), exactly as Handlebars <code>inverse</code>,
  Svelte <code>alternate</code>, Jinja <code>else_</code>, and estree <code>alternate</code> all do.
</blockquote>
<p>
  This is the canonical model, and it is what the recipe format should adopt over a <code>mid</code> scalar
  (zero prior art) or a nested <code>{{#else}}</code> region (zero prior art). The one true divergence — Liquid's
  flat <code>@blocks</code> list — is elegant for the n-way <code>elsif</code> chain but loses the distinct
  named-role clarity (an if-body and an else-body are different roles, not two instances of one). Adopting the
  named-programs model is a <strong>standard-layer contract change</strong> (a region's single <code>.content</code>
  becomes a named-program map), so #2201 should take it as a reversible #2074 model extension with lineage — not
  keep parking.
</p>

